    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so basically the steel is there to catch the cracks or something? can you explain how they physically bond together so they actually act as one unit instead of just sliding past each other inside the slab?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The steel doesn't actually \"catch\" the cracks in the sense of stopping them; rather, the rebar is placed *before* the concrete cures so it can carry tensile loads that would otherwise cause cracks to form in the first place. They bond together physically through high-friction hooks, straight tying wire, and the rough surface of standard rebar, which prevents them from sliding apart when the concrete hydrates. Once bound, they act as a monolithic unit, allowing the concrete and steel to share deformation and distribute stresses effectively under load.",
